# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: WarriorPath | Scene: WarriorQueen3
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah stood at the bow of her ship."
    new "Sarah stood at the bow of her ship."

    old "Above her, not a cloud in the sky."
    new "Above her, not a cloud in the sky."

    old "The stars and moon shined so bright that it hardly felt like night."
    new "The stars and moon shined so bright that it hardly felt like night."

    old "Around her, the ships of her armada sailed effortlessly across smooth water."
    new "Around her, the ships of her armada sailed effortlessly across smooth water."

    old "Bathed in the light of the moon, their sails were like sheets of silver."
    new "Bathed in the light of the moon, their sails were like sheets of silver."

    old "She heard the sounds of the sailors, rigging the ship for arrival."
    new "She heard the sounds of the sailors, rigging the ship for arrival."

    old "But their sounds were distant to her, as were all sensations."
    new "But their sounds were distant to her, as were all sensations."

    old "Out in the far distance, crawling across the horizon, Sarah saw the only thing that occupied her mind."
    new "Out in the far distance, crawling across the horizon, Sarah saw the only thing that occupied her mind."

    old "Land."
    new "Land."

    old "Her homeland."
    new "Her homeland."

    old "She had expected that it would move her, but she had not expected to feel everything that she was now feeling."
    new "She had expected that it would move her, but she had not expected to feel everything that she was now feeling."

    old "Sarah gripped the wooden railings of the boat so tight she thought she'd might break it."
    new "Sarah gripped the wooden railings of the boat so tight she thought she'd might break it."

    old "A cold wind rushed up to meet her as they neared closer to land; the shores quickly growing."
    new "A cold wind rushed up to meet her as they neared closer to land; the shores quickly growing."

    old "Rosanna always suffered the changing seasons sooner than most places."
    new "Rosanna always suffered the changing seasons sooner than most places."

    old "Sarah simply smiled."
    new "Sarah simply smiled."

    old "The cold winds grew colder, deeper. Soon, the cold frost winds felt like razors across her face."
    new "The cold winds grew colder, deeper. Soon, the cold frost winds felt like razors across her face."

    old "And yet, she only smiled."
    new "And yet, she only smiled."

    old "For how long had she missed this?"
    new "For how long had she missed this?"

    old "How many years had she secretly dreamed that she might feel her land as she had done in her youth."
    new "How many years had she secretly dreamed that she might feel her land as she had done in her youth."

    old "When she had fled across the sea, she had imagined she would return soon."
    new "When she had fled across the sea, she had imagined she would return soon."

    old "Then, when the years turned, she had instead imagined that it was forever lost to her, and she would never see her homeland again."
    new "Then, when the years turned, she had instead imagined that it was forever lost to her, and she would never see her homeland again."

    old "Now, with the pain from the wind on her face, she was happier than she had been for a long time."
    new "Now, with the pain from the wind on her face, she was happier than she had been for a long time."

    old "It reminded her that this was real."
    new "It reminded her that this was real."

    old "A dream she had murdered, returned so vividly that she could now feel it on her skin."
    new "A dream she had murdered, returned so vividly that she could now feel it on her skin."

    old "As they came closer to land, Sarah could increasingly make out the smaller details."
    new "As they came closer to land, Sarah could increasingly make out the smaller details."

    old "The beaches, the cliffsides that raised up so high."
    new "The beaches, the cliffsides that raised up so high."

    old "And among them, her soldiers."
    new "And among them, her soldiers."

    old "From this distance, they were still like ants."
    new "From this distance, they were still like ants."

    old "The first wave of her armada had set out ahead of the others, to secure a forward position."
    new "The first wave of her armada had set out ahead of the others, to secure a forward position."

    old "The Tribesmen might be weakened, but they were still formidable warriors. She could not risk an ambush."
    new "The Tribesmen might be weakened, but they were still formidable warriors. She could not risk an ambush."

    old "So instead, the vanguard had landed first and begun construction of a warcamp."
    new "So instead, the vanguard had landed first and begun construction of a warcamp."

    old "Judging by their busy movements, Sarah assumed they were likely well under way."
    new "Judging by their busy movements, Sarah assumed they were likely well under way."

    old "It was a good sign."
    new "It was a good sign."

    old "It meant that the Tribesmen had likely not spotted them yet."
    new "It meant that the Tribesmen had likely not spotted them yet."

    old "They had hoped this would be the case."
    new "They had hoped this would be the case."

    old "The Tribesmen were warriors, yes, but they were warriors of the land. The desert."
    new "The Tribesmen were warriors, yes, but they were warriors of the land. The desert."

    old "Their powerful cavalry offered no advantage against the sea. In fact, by most accounts, they had no navy to speak of. Not even boats for fishing."
    new "Their powerful cavalry offered no advantage against the sea. In fact, by most accounts, they had no navy to speak of. Not even boats for fishing."

    old "And with the years so long passed, they had ceased to fear an attack from the sea."
    new "And with the years so long passed, they had ceased to fear an attack from the sea."

    old "They had driven her out as a foolish girl, but she would return to them a warrior."
    new "They had driven her out as a foolish girl, but she would return to them a warrior."

    old "They had taught her a lesson. Now she would return the favor and teach the Tribes her lessons of war."
    new "They had taught her a lesson. Now she would return the favor and teach the Tribes her lessons of war."

    old "Finally, her ship neared as close as it could. Any closer and they would risk hitting land."
    new "Finally, her ship neared as close as it could. Any closer and they would risk hitting land."

    old "Sarah climbed onto the first small rowboat and allowed herself to be ferried to land."
    new "Sarah climbed onto the first small rowboat and allowed herself to be ferried to land."

    old "With the beating of the oars, striking hard against the surface of the water, Sarah felt her heart begin to race."
    new "With the beating of the oars, striking hard against the surface of the water, Sarah felt her heart begin to race."

    old "Faster, faster."
    new "Faster, faster."

    old "The land neared so close that she almost thought she could touch it."
    new "The land neared so close that she almost thought she could touch it."

    old "Then, leaping out from the rowboat in a moment of frenzy, Sarah waded into the sea."
    new "Then, leaping out from the rowboat in a moment of frenzy, Sarah waded into the sea."

    old "The waters rushed up to her stomach as she began to wade through the water."
    new "The waters rushed up to her stomach as she began to wade through the water."

    old "She could wait not a fraction more."
    new "She could wait not a fraction more."

    old "The cold did not faze her at all, instead, she felt the excitement burning in her chest."
    new "The cold did not faze her at all, instead, she felt the excitement burning in her chest."

    old "Rushing up the shoreline, Sarah stumbled out from the sea, onto dry land."
    new "Rushing up the shoreline, Sarah stumbled out from the sea, onto dry land."

    old "Instantly, she fell to her knees."
    new "Instantly, she fell to her knees."

    old "Digging her hands into the sand, she pulled it out and held it close to her face."
    new "Digging her hands into the sand, she pulled it out and held it close to her face."

    old "She could hardly believe it was real."
    new "She could hardly believe it was real."

    old "Around her, people cheered at the Princess reunited with her land."
    new "Around her, people cheered at the Princess reunited with her land."

    old "Sarah brought her hands up to her neck, pressing the sand against her neck."
    new "Sarah brought her hands up to her neck, pressing the sand against her neck."

    old "More than see the land, more than touch it, she needed to feel it."
    new "More than see the land, more than touch it, she needed to feel it."

    old "And at every moment, she was reminded how all of it was real."
    new "And at every moment, she was reminded how all of it was real."

    old "Tears ran down her face."
    new "Tears ran down her face."

    old "She was home."
    new "She was home."

    old "Sarah only had a brief moment to herself before one of her officers came to collect her."
    new "Sarah only had a brief moment to herself before one of her officers came to collect her."

    old "Commander, the war room is ready for you."
    new "Commander, the war room is ready for you."

    old "Sarah briefly nodded."
    new "Sarah briefly nodded."

    old "Excellent, take me there immediately."
    new "Excellent, take me there immediately."

    old "Walking with a great pace, Sarah followed the officer and made her way through the camp."
    new "Walking with a great pace, Sarah followed the officer and made her way through the camp."

    old "It was rough, but they had only just landed. It was a miracle there was even anything to be critical about."
    new "It was rough, but they had only just landed. It was a miracle there was even anything to be critical about."

    old "Soon, perhaps in little more than a day or so, it would be proper camp."
    new "Soon, perhaps in little more than a day or so, it would be proper camp."

    old "As she made her way towards the main tent, she could see out towards far ends of the camp."
    new "As she made her way towards the main tent, she could see out towards far ends of the camp."

    old "Trenches, dug over a meter deep, lined with sharpend spikes."
    new "Trenches, dug over a meter deep, lined with sharpend spikes."

    old "They would break any cavalry charge."
    new "They would break any cavalry charge."

    old "Sarah stepped into the commander's tent."
    new "Sarah stepped into the commander's tent."

    old "As she entered, she heard the murmurs go quiet."
    new "As she entered, she heard the murmurs go quiet."

    old "All as one, everyone turned to face her."
    new "All as one, everyone turned to face her."

    old "Sarah wasn't unfamiliar with taking command, but until not that long ago it had been Vaelen who took center stage."
    new "Sarah wasn't unfamiliar with taking command, but until not that long ago it had been Vaelen who took center stage."

    old "She still struggled with her new role."
    new "She still struggled with her new role."

    old "Sarah strode forward, making sure to hide any signs of the doubt she harbored within."
    new "Sarah strode forward, making sure to hide any signs of the doubt she harbored within."

    old "In the center of the room was a large map showing the lands of Rosanna. Some figurines, carved from wood, represented the armies."
    new "In the center of the room was a large map showing the lands of Rosanna. Some figurines, carved from wood, represented the armies."

    old "Most of her own were clustered around the beaches, near her warcamp."
    new "Most of her own were clustered around the beaches, near her warcamp."

    old "Spread across the rest of Rosanna, figures that carried the mark of the Tribes."
    new "Spread across the rest of Rosanna, figures that carried the mark of the Tribes."

    old "Catch me up, has anything changed since we left Rahayal?"
    new "Catch me up, has anything changed since we left Rahayal?"

    old "Sarah, together with her commanders and officers had spend weeks coming up with a strategy."
    new "Sarah, together with her commanders and officers had spend weeks coming up with a strategy."

    old "But Sarah knew as well as anyone that when it came to war, the reality on the ground was often changing faster than the plans did."
    new "But Sarah knew as well as anyone that when it came to war, the reality on the ground was often changing faster than the plans did."

    old "The vanguard, lead by Gideon, had landed a few days before she had, setting up the warcamp."
    new "The vanguard, lead by Gideon, had landed a few days before she had, setting up the warcamp."

    old "They would know the most recent information."
    new "They would know the most recent information."

    old "Gideon walked up to the table."
    new "Gideon walked up to the table."

    old "We've nearly finished setting up camp."
    new "We've nearly finished setting up camp."

    old "He placed his finger on the table near the beach where they had constructed the camp."
    new "He placed his finger on the table near the beach where they had constructed the camp."

    old "We've not been able to move out too much into the interior. We still need a lot of the men to help unloading the ships."
    new "We've not been able to move out too much into the interior. We still need a lot of the men to help unloading the ships."

    old "The vanguard had landed first, but they were only a small part of her army."
    new "The vanguard had landed first, but they were only a small part of her army."

    old "It would be days more before the rest of her army made land."
    new "It would be days more before the rest of her army made land."

    old "Then they would have to disembark. They would have to unload their provisions, their gear. Then they'd have to make camp themselves."
    new "Then they would have to disembark. They would have to unload their provisions, their gear. Then they'd have to make camp themselves."

    old "Simply landing thousands of men was an entire operation by itself."
    new "Simply landing thousands of men was an entire operation by itself."

    old "Sarah tapped the map."
    new "Sarah tapped the map."

    old "What about the Tribesmen?"
    new "What about the Tribesmen?"

    old "Have we spotted any yet?"
    new "Have we spotted any yet?"

    old "Gideon shook his head."
    new "Gideon shook his head."

    old "We've sound out a few forward scouts."
    new "We've sound out a few forward scouts."

    old "He tapped the map, showing the most outwardly positioned figurines."
    new "He tapped the map, showing the most outwardly positioned figurines."

    old "They've taken position on nearby hills, but so far, they report nothing."
    new "They've taken position on nearby hills, but so far, they report nothing."

    old "Sarah contemplated her position."
    new "Sarah contemplated her position."

    old "This moment, right now, was when she would be most vulnerable."
    new "This moment, right now, was when she would be most vulnerable."

    old "Part of her army on land, part still on sea. Her defenses only partially up."
    new "Part of her army on land, part still on sea. Her defenses only partially up."

    old "If the Tribesmen had spotted her army and prepared an attack, they would be unable to even retreat, blocked in by the sea."
    new "If the Tribesmen had spotted her army and prepared an attack, they would be unable to even retreat, blocked in by the sea."

    old "Any signs that we've been detected?"
    new "Any signs that we've been detected?"

    old "So far, nothing."
    new "So far, nothing."

    old "We haven't spotted any Tribesmen patrols, but then again, we have been keeping quite close to the shore."
    new "We haven't spotted any Tribesmen patrols, but then again, we have been keeping quite close to the shore."

    old "Sarah studied the map. It was true that even the most forward scouts were not that deep inland."
    new "Sarah studied the map. It was true that even the most forward scouts were not that deep inland."

    old "She tapped the map with her finger near the symbol of a city."
    new "She tapped the map with her finger near the symbol of a city."

    old "The city of Ridgehaven."
    new "The city of Ridgehaven."

    old "What about Ridgehaven? What has been the report there?"
    new "What about Ridgehaven? What has been the report there?"

    old "Gideon looked at her."
    new "Gideon looked at her."

    old "We don't know."
    new "We don't know."

    old "No. So far, we've held back. Our main priority has been to avoid detection, so we held back. Even the scouts were told to stay near camp."
    new "No. So far, we've held back. Our main priority has been to avoid detection, so we held back. Even the scouts were told to stay near camp."

    old "Sarah understood the strategy, but she worried regardless."
    new "Sarah understood the strategy, but she worried regardless."

    old "By not scouting further ahead, it meant that the Tribesmen might be setting up on them, only a few miles from here."
    new "By not scouting further ahead, it meant that the Tribesmen might be setting up on them, only a few miles from here."

    old "The city of Ridgehaven was a midsized town that sat upon a river that ran out to the sea. Mostly fishermen and merchants."
    new "The city of Ridgehaven was a midsized town that sat upon a river that ran out to the sea. Mostly fishermen and merchants."

    old "It wasn't vital to reclaiming Rosanna, but it might tell them a lot about what was happening in the country."
    new "It wasn't vital to reclaiming Rosanna, but it might tell them a lot about what was happening in the country."

    old "Most of the reports that Sarah had available to her were months old. Valuable information, but possibly out of date."
    new "Most of the reports that Sarah had available to her were months old. Valuable information, but possibly out of date."

    old "We could send a scout party up the road to Ridgehaven. See what is going on there."
    new "We could send a scout party up the road to Ridgehaven. See what is going on there."

    old "We could, but if there are Tribesmen loyalists or spies, they might report back to the capital."
    new "We could, but if there are Tribesmen loyalists or spies, they might report back to the capital."

    old "The idea of sympathizers to the Tribesmen had seemed absurd to her."
    new "The idea of sympathizers to the Tribesmen had seemed absurd to her."

    old "But the truth was that most people, even in Rosanna, were only loyal up to a point."
    new "But the truth was that most people, even in Rosanna, were only loyal up to a point."

    old "When the Tribesmen took over and became the ruling power, it shouldn't have surprised her that more than a few people would try to benefit from it."
    new "When the Tribesmen took over and became the ruling power, it shouldn't have surprised her that more than a few people would try to benefit from it."

    old "And what was the use in staying loyal to a royal family that was dead or had fled?"
    new "And what was the use in staying loyal to a royal family that was dead or had fled?"

    old "Sarah sighed. She felt guilt over her own journey across the sea."
    new "Sarah sighed. She felt guilt over her own journey across the sea."

    old "She had not fled, not intentionally, but people might very well read her actions as such."
    new "She had not fled, not intentionally, but people might very well read her actions as such."

    old "And she didn't feel as if she could blame them for think that either."
    new "And she didn't feel as if she could blame them for think that either."

    old "Sarah studied the map again."
    new "Sarah studied the map again."

    old "Sending a scout party to investigate Ridgehaven in secret could gain them valuable information."
    new "Sending a scout party to investigate Ridgehaven in secret could gain them valuable information."

    old "But if they were discovered, it could mean they'd be detected."
    new "But if they were discovered, it could mean they'd be detected."

    old "Send a scout party to infiltrate Ridgehaven"
    new "Send a scout party to infiltrate Ridgehaven"

    old "Sarah looked at Gideon."
    new "Sarah looked at Gideon."

    old "Send out a small unit of scouts to Ridgehaven."
    new "Send out a small unit of scouts to Ridgehaven."

    old "Tell them to leave their armor and sigils here, move undercover, then report back what they find."
    new "Tell them to leave their armor and sigils here, move undercover, then report back what they find."

    old "Yes, Commander. I'll tell the men."
    new "Yes, Commander. I'll tell the men."

    old "Tell the scouts to stay near camp"
    new "Tell the scouts to stay near camp"

    old "Let it rest for now. The first priority is that we remain undetected."
    new "Let it rest for now. The first priority is that we remain undetected."

    old "Tell the scouts to remain close to camp."
    new "Tell the scouts to remain close to camp."

    old "Of course, I'll make sure to let the men know."
    new "Of course, I'll make sure to let the men know."

    old "Sarah looked at the map again."
    new "Sarah looked at the map again."

    old "Well, that settles the most pressing issue, but what about the longer term goals?"
    new "Well, that settles the most pressing issue, but what about the longer term goals?"

    old "Gideon pointed at the map again."
    new "Gideon pointed at the map again."

    old "We expect to finish preparin the last defenses in the coming days."
    new "We expect to finish preparin the last defenses in the coming days."

    old "A few more days after that, we expect most of your remaining troops to have landed and begun preparing."
    new "A few more days after that, we expect most of your remaining troops to have landed and begun preparing."

    old "It will take a while to gear everyone up and hand down orders, but after that, we should be ready to move."
    new "It will take a while to gear everyone up and hand down orders, but after that, we should be ready to move."

    old "So at best...a week or so?"
    new "So at best...a week or so?"

    old "We hope so."
    new "We hope so."

    old "His fingers moved along one of the roads on the map."
    new "His fingers moved along one of the roads on the map."

    old "This here is the main road that runs closest from our current position."
    new "This here is the main road that runs closest from our current position."

    old "It runs along Ridgehaven, deeper into the interior of Rosanna, all the way up to the capital."
    new "It runs along Ridgehaven, deeper into the interior of Rosanna, all the way up to the capital."

    old "Sarah studied it as Gideon ran his finger along it."
    new "Sarah studied it as Gideon ran his finger along it."

    old "Most of this area is grassland, the occasional small farmstead."
    new "Most of this area is grassland, the occasional small farmstead."

    old "We can move some units through it, but only the main road is going to be developed enough for us to move a real army across."
    new "We can move some units through it, but only the main road is going to be developed enough for us to move a real army across."

    old "A real army, the kind she had, was more than just men and horses."
    new "A real army, the kind she had, was more than just men and horses."

    old "The army needed supplies, and in case it came down to a siege, they'd even need to deploy some of the few siege weapons she had available to her."
    new "The army needed supplies, and in case it came down to a siege, they'd even need to deploy some of the few siege weapons she had available to her."

    old "All of which required a solid reliable road to transport."
    new "All of which required a solid reliable road to transport."

    old "If the road is cut-off, we'll be stuck."
    new "If the road is cut-off, we'll be stuck."

    old "Yes, and with the season turning, we expect snow to be falling soon. Likely within days."
    new "Yes, and with the season turning, we expect snow to be falling soon. Likely within days."

    old "That will likely slow us down."
    new "That will likely slow us down."

    old "Their army relies heavily on horses, so we suspect the snow will harm them just as much, if not more."
    new "Their army relies heavily on horses, so we suspect the snow will harm them just as much, if not more."

    old "But they've also been here for a few years."
    new "But they've also been here for a few years."

    old "They know the seasons as well as anyone by now. It's possible that they've adapted."
    new "They know the seasons as well as anyone by now. It's possible that they've adapted."

    old "Sarah continued to study the map."
    new "Sarah continued to study the map."

    old "It's equally possible they've locked themselves into the cities and grown fat from their looting, having learned nothing about our land."
    new "It's equally possible they've locked themselves into the cities and grown fat from their looting, having learned nothing about our land."

    old "Yes, that too is possible, but we can't say either way."
    new "Yes, that too is possible, but we can't say either way."

    old "Sarah tapped the map again."
    new "Sarah tapped the map again."

    old "This will be what matters most on our advance."
    new "This will be what matters most on our advance."

    old "Beneath her finger rested the city of Calshure. It was the only truly major city that stood between them and the capital."
    new "Beneath her finger rested the city of Calshure. It was the only truly major city that stood between them and the capital."

    old "If we capture it early, it secures our road to the capital. If we fail and end up in a long siege..."
    new "If we capture it early, it secures our road to the capital. If we fail and end up in a long siege..."

    old "Gideon nodded, a grim expression on his face."
    new "Gideon nodded, a grim expression on his face."

    old "Yes. Calshure is a hub for all the medium and small towns in the area. All the farmsteads converge there for their trading."
    new "Yes. Calshure is a hub for all the medium and small towns in the area. All the farmsteads converge there for their trading."

    old "If we take it, we secure food for your army and a road straight to the capital."
    new "If we take it, we secure food for your army and a road straight to the capital."

    old "He paused for a brief moment."
    new "He paused for a brief moment."

    old "But it is equally possible the enemy knows this."
    new "But it is equally possible the enemy knows this."

    old "If they shut the gates, we could be looking at a long siege."
    new "If they shut the gates, we could be looking at a long siege."

    old "And that would just be Calshure. All cities beyond, the capital included, would likely be reinforced by the time we take Calshure."
    new "And that would just be Calshure. All cities beyond, the capital included, would likely be reinforced by the time we take Calshure."

    old "Taking the city was obviously important...but perhaps it was too important. A trap that her enemy thought too impossible for her to pass on."
    new "Taking the city was obviously important...but perhaps it was too important. A trap that her enemy thought too impossible for her to pass on."

    old "What if we don't?"
    new "What if we don't?"

    old "Sarah drew her finger around the city of Calshure."
    new "Sarah drew her finger around the city of Calshure."

    old "What if we avoid the city by moving along this road?"
    new "What if we avoid the city by moving along this road?"

    old "That's a side branch to the main road."
    new "That's a side branch to the main road."

    old "It's less developped and not as wide as the main road. Moving across it would slow our army, but it would allow us to avoid Calshure."
    new "It's less developped and not as wide as the main road. Moving across it would slow our army, but it would allow us to avoid Calshure."

    old "However, that would also mean we would lose out on having Calshure as a source of supplies for the army."
    new "However, that would also mean we would lose out on having Calshure as a source of supplies for the army."

    old "He studied the map for a moment."
    new "He studied the map for a moment."

    old "However, it would create for an interesting chance."
    new "However, it would create for an interesting chance."

    old "We move through the hinterlands and come out on the western side of the capital."
    new "We move through the hinterlands and come out on the western side of the capital."

    old "If we succeed, we have the element of surprise."
    new "If we succeed, we have the element of surprise."

    old "If we fail, we lose many precious days, are low on supplies, and we attack the capital from an inferior direction."
    new "If we fail, we lose many precious days, are low on supplies, and we attack the capital from an inferior direction."

    old "It was true, Sarah remembered. The land on the western side of the capital ran far lower, almost like a valley. They would literally be fighting uphill."
    new "It was true, Sarah remembered. The land on the western side of the capital ran far lower, almost like a valley. They would literally be fighting uphill."

    old "Yet...if we take them by surprise, it might make up for the layout of the land."
    new "Yet...if we take them by surprise, it might make up for the layout of the land."

    old "And we don't risk getting stuck on the city of Calshure."
    new "And we don't risk getting stuck on the city of Calshure."

    old "I will have to consider this."
    new "I will have to consider this."

    old "Of course. We don't need to make a decision right away, we still have a week or so before we are set to march."
    new "Of course. We don't need to make a decision right away, we still have a week or so before we are set to march."

    old "A week."
    new "A week."

    old "It both felt too long and too short at the same time to Sarah."
    new "It both felt too long and too short at the same time to Sarah."

    old "Well done for now, Gideon."
    new "Well done for now, Gideon."

    old "Go oversee the continued construction of the camp."
